TY  - JOUR
T1  - Discrete Approximations of Probability Distributions
AU  - Miller, Allen C.
AU  - Rice, Thomas R.
Y1  - 1983/03/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.29.3.352
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.29.3.352
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 352
EP  - 362
VL  - 29
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Practical limits on the size of most probabilistic models require that probability distributions be approximated by a few representative values and associated probabilities. This paper demonstrates that methods commonly used to determine discrete approximations of probability distributions systematically underestimate the moments of the original distribution. A new procedure based on gaussian quadrature is developed in this paper. It can be used to decrease the error in the approximation to any desired level.
AB  - Practical limits on the size of most probabilistic models require that probability distributions be approximated by a few representative values and associated probabilities. This paper demonstrates that methods commonly used to determine discrete approximations of probability distributions systematically underestimate the moments of the original distribution. A new procedure based on gaussian quadrature is developed in this paper. It can be used to decrease the error in the approximation to any desired level.
